{"/service/ndnp/sdhi/batch_sdhi_guava_ver02/data/sn85042792/00332899946/1920123001/0087.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE TWO\nP\ni\n<s>\nThe New Year is Here\n\u2014let us hail it with joy\n\u2014the return of prosperity\n\u2014the light of brighter days\n\u2014hopes of a rosy future\nMay we merit a continuation of the support\naccorded us in the past\nBrookings Creamery\nI. J. Bibby, Manager\nCORRESPONDENCE\nA\u25a0!v i t isi innntH In tbl\u201d I'imn are 10 cents\np. iit>\", our orn apondentH will take your\nolder and niuat remit at the aamu time,\notherwise tiny will not b\" published.\nWINSOR OAKWOOD\nMr. ami Mrs Ole Ericson ami chil\ndren were visitors at tho Christ\nThompson home Saturday.\nMiss Kathryn Daum, John and Will\nDaum wire among the number who\nwere entertained at the ('has Reeves\nhome Sunday last.\nMr. and Mrs. Oscar Lee, Mr. and\nMrs. August Nel on. Mr. and Mrs.\nJalmer Vostad of Volga, Miss Ida\nNelson, Mr. and Mrs. Chris Nelson,\nMr. and Mrs. F. W. Williams and Mr.\nami Mrs. Harry Nelson were enter\ntained at the C. E. Walston home on\nChristmas day.\nMiss Clara Bacon is pending the\nholidays at the Thomas Fish home in\nBrookings.\nC. W. Jones and E. A. Bacon spent\nChristmas at the Geo. Ericson home.\nSeveral from this vicinity attended\nthe Christmas tree and program given\nat the Sterling church Sunday evening.\nA number of relatives were enter\ntained at the J. W. Barker home last\nSaturday.\nMr. and Mrs. Geo. Ericson and chil\ndren and Halleck Halleckson spent\nSunday at August Nelson\u2019s.\nJ. W. Parker transacted business at\nBruce Friday.\nWill Nelson was a Brookings vis\nitor last Thursday and Friday.\nw. 8. s.\nSTERLING\nMiss Tillie Peterson of Seattle,\nWash., returned to her home last\nweek after several months\u2019 visit in\nthe homes of her sisters-in-law, Mrs.\nAugust Peterson and Mrs. Emma\nPeterson.\nArnold Olson assisted Wright Gru\ndem with butchering last Thursday.\nJohn Hastings marketed hogs in\nBruce last Friday.\nHenry Olson of Firesteel is a guest\nin the Olson home.\nTheodore Rude departed last week\nfor Armour to spend Christmas with\nhis sister and her husband, Mr. and\nMrs. Roy Crisman.\nMr and Mrs. John Hastings spent\nChristmas with Mrs. Hastings\u2019 par\nents, Mr. and Mrs. Rufer, in Brook\nings. i\n24 Hour a Day\nElectric Service\nai 4\nho\nMl\ndelcought\nDelco-Light is made for long,\ndependable and efficient service.\nTh\u00ab best mechanics are em\nployed in the factory where\nDelco-Light Is made. Only the\nbest of materials are used and\neach plant is repeatedly tested\nbefore being shipped.\nWrite for Catalog\nHeymer Electric\nPHONE* \u2014BROOKINGS,\nL\nI\nI m\nfeu*\nevery\nMrs. Emma Peterson ami family,\nAlfred Peterson and his mother were\ndinner guests on Christmas day in\nthe home of Mis. August Peterson.\nOlotis 01-on and Henry Olson were\ncallers al Wright Grudem\u2019s one after\nnoon last Week.\nGrant Rude and Clifford Girton\ncalled on the Peterson boy- Sunday\nafternoon.\n\\dolph Odegard of McArthur, N. D,\narrived home Sunday for a visit with\nIn- lather, Albert odegard and other\nrelatives.\nMr. and Mrs. Lyman Hastings spent\nChristmas in Brookings at the J. B.\nHastings home.\nNels Oiness is able to be out again\nalter being quarantined a short time\nwith smallpox.\nChristmas exercises were held in\nthe Sterling Lutheran church Sunday\nI\nevening. An exeelent program was\ngiven.\nSOUTH OAKWOOD\nMr. and Mrs. A. H. Stinehart and\nlametta and Earl and Ed. Schwartz\nwere visitors at the John Fish home\nnear Watertown last Sunday.\nJohn, Will and Kate Daum spent\nSunday at the Charles Reeves home\nnear Volga.\nMr. and Mrs. Frank Rumple and\nfamily were dinner guests at Charles\nSmith\u2019s on hristmas.\nMr. and Mrs. George Erickson anil\nchildren spent Sunday at August Nel\nson\u2019s.\nThe Misses Lillian, Ethel and Myrtle\nKrumm spent one evening last week\nt.t the Daum home.\nMen\u2019s four-buckle overshoes $3.85\nat the Boot Shop.\nMrs. John Wabbema returned last\nSunday after spending some time at\nthe Saulken home near Watertown.\nMiss Myrtle Woodard is spending a\ntwo weeks\u2019 vacation at her home in\nVolga.\nw. s. s.\nPRESTON\nMiss Teresa Davenport left last\nThursday evening for Staples, Minn.,\nto spend the holiday vacation with\nrelatives.\nMr. and Mrs. F. C. Shaw were Wa\ntertown visitors last Monday.\nWil| Nelson of Chicago, is visiting\nin the home of his sister, Mrs. O. T.\nLee.\nMr. and Mrs. I ver Reppe and Mr.\nand Mrs. Wm. Grieme spent Christmas\nin the Andrew Reppe home.\nMr. and Mrs. James Carbine were\nChristmas dinner guests at the home\nof D. M. Ax ford.\nMr. and Mrs. O. T. Lee spent a few\ndays of this weelc visiting at the Perry\nClifford home near Cresbard.\nMiss Eunice Cotton left Tuesday to\nresume her studies at the Madison\nState Normal.\nMr. and Mrs. C. W. Loomis and fam\nily spent Christmas in Estelline in the\nG. T. Lee home.\nw. s. s.\nAURORA\nHomer Rexford of Brookings was\ncalling on relatives in Aurora Tuesday.\nMrs. Geo. Baker and son Edwin left\nThursday evening for Spring Valley,\nMinn., to spend Christmas with Mrs.\nBaker's parents, Mr. and Mrs. A.\nBaldwin.\nMr. and Mrs. E. D. Southard and\nsons, Vernon and Emeroy, left Thurs\nday noon for Mason City to spend\nChristmas with Mr. Southard\u2019s mother.\nMrs. E. W. Rufenacht and children of\nMinot, N. D., intends to be there also.\nMrs. Rufenacht is Mr. Southard's sis\nter.\nV. R. Welch, county treasurer, was\nin Aurora Tuesday.\nMr. and Mrs. H. A. Pike called at\nthe O. F. Short home Tuesday after\nnoon.\nMrs. J. W. Collins and family spent\nChristmas day at the Jas. Thompson\nhome in Brookings.\nMr. and Mrs. F. I. Neal spent Christ\nmas at the Fred C. Ortner home in\nWatertown.\nCo.\nD.\nTHE BROOKINGS REGISTER, BROOKINGS, S. 11. TIIURS DAY. DECEMBER 30, 1920.\nChas. Gaukcl made a business trip\nto Brookings Monday afternoon.\nMrs Mary Johnson and daughter\nMamie went to Redfield last week to\n.-pend Christmas with the Ed. Crite\nfamily.\nGeorge Ripley of Thomas, S. D., is\nvisiting hr- grandmother, Mrs. C. S.\nRipley, during the holidays.\nMr. and Mrs. C. E. Korte spent\nChristmas day at the Thos. Enright\nhome in Brookings.\nMr. and Mrs. F. J. Formonek and\nson Alden left last Thursday for Belle\nPlain, la., where they will remain a\ncouple of weeks visiting relatives.\nMr and Mrs. Roy Parks and little\ndaughter went to Milltown, Win.,\nwhere they will spend a few weeks\n!at Mr. Parks\u2019 parents. Mr. Parks\u2019 sis\nter who has been visiting them re\nturned to Milltown.\nMiss Gladys Phillips has been ill\nthe last few days, but is better now\nJ W. Trail is on the sick list this\nweek.\nMen\u2019s four-buckle overshoes $3.85\nat the Boot Shop.\nC. O. Kirby is ill this week.\nI Donald Carson, who attends college\nin Brookings, assisted W. G. Ray dur\nj ing Christmas week.\nMr. and Mrs. Theo. Pederson of\nj Brookings, are visiting at the A. B.\nj Hendricks home.\nFrancis Collins is home from Sioux\n1 Falls for the Christmas holidays.\nThe Christmas program and tree\nheld at the church Friday evening\nwas att< nded by a large crowd and\neveryone enjoyed the delightful music\nami speaking.\nHird McKinney of Brookings, wa\nin Aurora Tuesday.\nMr and Mr-. J. G. McClemans were\nentertained Christmas at the G. L.\nloodrich home.\nJ. Vanausdale of Detroit. Minn., 1-\nI here visiting friends.\nMiss Lucile Baker returned to Ma.li\nson Tuesday evening after her Christ\nmas vacation.\nw. s. s.\nALTON\nThe Charles Potter family were\nI shopping in Brookings Friday.\nDonald McMillan and Walter Burn\nham ate Christmas dinner with home\nfolks.\ni.Mss Olga Oleson closed school for\nthe holidays Friday.\nBernie Felton is helping out on the\nmail route these cold days; and the\nroads are poor, too.\nSeveral from this community a\u2019\ntended the week end Christmas fes\ntivities at Brookings.\nw. s. s.\nNORTH BROOKINGS\nMr. and Mrs. Charles Keck enter\ntained their relatives at Christmas din\nner at their home on Sunday.\nF. B. Smith and family ate Christ\nmas dinner at the home of Mrs.\nSmith\u2019s sister. Mrs. Alma Prunty in\nBrookings Saturday.\nRoy Ullman returned Wednesday\nfrom a visit to his old home at Paul\nlina. la.\nRobert Goff of Paullina, la., arrived\n.Monday for a visit at the Guy Smith\nand Bruce McAfee homes.\nRoscoe and Edgar Searles and fam\nilies spent Christmas at the C. A.\nSearles home in Brookings.\nJ. W. Lane and family spent Christ\nmas day at the Dr. E. H. Whitehead\nhome in Brookings.\nMen\u2019s four-buckle overshoes $3.85\nat the Boot Shop.\nThe Community club will hold their\nnext meeting at the James Sloan. Jr.,\nhome Friday evening, December 31.\nThe married ladies will give a pro\ngram. Everybody welcome.\nGuy Smith and family spent Christ\nmas at the Bruce McAfee home.\nLloyd Schroeder and family ate\nChristmas dinner at the George Fenn\nhome in Brookings.\nMr. and Mrs. John Gile are the\nproud parents of a daughter, born\nMonday, December 27.\nWord was received last week from\nMr. and Mrs. E. A. Tatge of Luverne,\nMinn., that they have another son.\nborn Thanksgiving day, November 25.\nMrs. C. P. Scott has been visiting\nin Sioux Falls the past week.\nFOUNTAIN\nMr. and Mrs. August Swanson and\nfamily, Mr. and Mrs. Frank Swanson\nand children, Mr. and Mrs. A. G. Lun\ndeen and family and Mr. and Mrs. Glen\nLundeen were Christmas guests in the\nBuettner home.\nAlbert Jessen spent Christmas with\nhis parents, Mr. and Mrs. Stephen.\nMr. and Mrs. Clare Green and chil\ndren spent Friday night and Saturday\nat the Glen Collins home, south of\nAurora.\nThe George Garrison family enter\ntained Mr. and Mrs. Harry Felton and\nfamily, Kenneth Mills and Leslie\nSoden at Christmas dinner,\nMr. and Mrs. Gail Seas and Frank\nHussey spent Sunday at the Bane\nhome.\nClarence Stephen visited his brother,\nAlbert Jessen, this week.\nThe pupils of Fountain No. 7 gave\ntheir Christmas program on Thurs\nday evening. A big feature was the\nChristmas tree on which the children\nreceived nuts and candy.\nMr. and Mrs. Engel and family\ncalled at the M. Nussbaum home on\nSaturday evening.\nw. s. s.\nEld\u00bbn Felton vi.-ited his cousin,\nLloyd Garrison, this week.\nMrs. C. Blakeslee and family were\nentertain'd at the home of her sister.\nMi.-. S. Selix, over Christmas.\nMr and Mrs. Ray Shank and son\nate Christmas dinner at the Dupraz\nhome.\nMen\u2019s four-buckle overshoes $3.85\nat the Boot Shop.\nWayne Garrison spent a few days\nthe first of the week at the Harry\nFelton home east of Bushnell.\nMr. and Mrs. Ralph Seas and boys\nspent Christmas at the Frank Dulf\nhome in Brookings.\nMr and Mrs. Nussbaum and family\nvi-ited the Louis Eberlein home on\nSaturday.\nMisses Lulu and Gertrude Buettner\nan visiting relatives in Fountain dur\ning the Christmas vacation.\nFloyd Engel called on Albert Jes\nsen Sunday afternoon.\nMiss Lizzie Telkamp spent from\nThursday until Monday at the home\nof her parents.\nMr. and Mrs. Daniel Beals and\ndaughter of Brookings, spent Christ\nmas at the home of the latter\u2019s father,\nLouis Eberle.n.\nMr. and Mrs. George McMillan of\nHardwick, Minn., are the proud par\nents of a baby boy, born December 15.\nMrs. McMillan was formerly Miss\nEllen Bane of this place.\nMiss Agnes Carlson was a guest at\nthe Vaselaar home last week.\nA few Fountamites attended the\nprogram and handkerchief social at\ntie Alton school house on Wednes\nday evening.\nMrs. Frank Hussey and son Donald\nft Monday for Hardwick. Minn.,\nwhere she will visit her sister, Mrs.\nGeorge McMillan.\nw. s. s.\nBUSHNELL\nThe Christmas program which was\niven by the Bushnell public school\nn the Grange hall, Wednesday even\ntig. vvas a great success. It was well\nit tended in spite of the bad weather.\nI'he tine program which was given\n.ts enjoyed by all. After the pro\ngram gifts which were put on the\nChristmas tree were distributed and\nandy and apples were given to every\n:-:son. Congratulations to the teach\ners and pupils of this school for their\nsplendid entertainment.\nVera Olson, who is attending the\nMadison State Normal, is spending\nh'-r Christmas vacation with home\nfolks.\nGordon Miller and Robert Yeske de\nparted Friday for Biglow, Minn.\nKatherine Armstrong and Georgia\nFelton were shopping in Elkton be\ntween trains Friday.\nHarry Bailey and Wesley Elston\nmade a busiess trip to Brookings Fri\nday.\nMen\u2019s four-buckle overshoes $3.85\nat the Boot Shop.\nMiss Violet Stanley and Emil White\nof Watertown, arrived here Friday for\na visit at the Laurence White home.\nMrs. Fred Baker of Redfield, ar\nrived Thursday for a visit with her\nparents. Mr. and Mrs. F. E. Judd of\nthis place.\nMr. and Mrs. A. M. Tiahrt of this\nplace spent Christmas at Watertown\nat the home of Mrs. Tiahrt\u2019s parents.\nJanies Klimes, section foreman of\nJasper, Minn., spent Christmas with\nhis family at Bushnell.\nTHE UNIVERSAL CAR\nThe Ford Sedan\nThis splendid car is growing more popular every day, because every\nday the demand for the enclosed car increases in volume, and when you\nthink that the Ford Sedan, with all its comforts and conveniences an\nenclosed car, handsome in appearance, roomy for five passengers, nicely\nupholstered, sliding plate glass windows which make it an open car in\na minute or so or a tightly closed car that is dust-proof and water-proof\nready for service every day of the year, rain or shine, summer or winter,\nand then think that thia car is lower in price than any touring car (except\nthe Ford car) \"and you will not wonder that we ask you to leave you r\norder for a Sedan as soon as possible that we may be able to give you\nreasonable delivery.\nOf course, you cannot forget that matchless and reliable \u201cFord After-\nService\u201d that follows every Ford car the world over\u2014always within arm\u2019s\nlength a reliable Ford dealer or authorized Ford garage than can tune\nup your car and keep It In running condition every day in the year.\nWe want your trade.\nFarrington-Vessey-Conover\nWord was received from Ellsworth,\nMinn., of the arrival of a son at the\nhome of Mr. and Mrs. Geo. Ormrod,\nformerly of Bushnell.\nChurch Notes\u2014Sunday school, 10 a.\nm morning worship, 11 a. m.; even\ning worship, 7:30 p. in.; prayer meet\ning, Wednesday evening, 7:30 p. m.\nAll are cordially invited. Rev. Wm.\nDonaldson, pastor.\nMr. and Mrs. Guy Julian of Mitchell,\nspent Christmas with Mrs. Julian\u2019s\nparents, Mr. and Mrs. John Poppingo\nof this place.\nFred Elston of Montana, arrived\nhere Tuesday for a visit with his par\nents, Mr. and Mrs. S. B. Elston.\nMr. and Mrs. Charles Bain and fam\nily, Mr. and Mrs. Walter Bain and\nfamily ate Christmas dinner at the\nHarry Bailey home.\nMrs. Iva Bailey and daughter, Doris,\ndeparted Friday for Jasper, Minn.,\nwhere they expect to visit at the home\nof their daughter and sister, Mrs.\nLloyd Nelson.\nw. s. s.\nMEDARY\nHappy New Year.\nMrs. Sam Jansen is improving very\nslowly.\nAdolph Tonsager\u2019s father and mother\nfrom Sioux Falls are making him a\nvisit din ing the Christmas vacation.\nMarie Dancer has recovered from\nscarlet fever.\nJ. F. Jenks was delivering hogs in\nBrookings Wednesday.\nJohn Nieman has been hauling corn\nthis week and he found the roads very\nbad Monday.\nMr. and Mrs. Carl Trygstad enter\ntained at their home Tuesday evening\nthe Chas. Hawkins, Fred Polseau and\nJames Jenks families. Refreshments\nwere served and a fine time was en\njoyed by all.\nTonsager brothers are husking corn\nfor Carl Trygstad.\nDo You.\nUse Good Paper When\nYou Write?\nWe Can Print Anything\nand Do Pipht.\n&&Bs3cisi'SiiiSi; 'l~ Sir ?i?\nState Sale and Eighteenth Annual Meeting of\nSOUTH DAKOTA IMPROVED LIVESTOCK\nAND POULTRY BREEDER\u2019S ASSOCIATION\nFour big days of contim. ms activities\nHerefords, January 11th. J. 11. Sinclair, Beresford, Manager\nPoland Chinas, January 11th. Geo. Thiel, Alexandria.\nShorthorns, January 12th. M. J. Flanagan, Selby.\nPolled Shorthorns, January 13th. C. \\V. Stanley, Dolton\nDuroe Jerseys, January 13th. A. L. Haynes, Mitchell.\nChester Whites. January 14th. C. W. Caskey, Mitchell\nOfficial meetings of all breed associations during the week of the sales.\nMeetings of State Association of Poultrymen and Veterinarians. Big ban\nquet evening of January 12th to all members. Business meeting Janu\nary 14th.\nCome and Meet the Breeders.\nMITCHELL 7.NUARY 11. 12, 13 AND 14\nS -W?\nLilies, poinsettas, cyclamen and\nferns make acceptable Christmas\npresents. Cut Howers, such as roses\nor carnations, may also be used. A\ndozen gladiolus bulbs from on?'.- own\ngarden makes a year-round gift much\nappreciated by one who has a garden.\nHeWas Broke\nand Away\nFrom Home\nMarooned in one\nof those queer, ever\nturbulent Central\nAmerica republics,\nBilly Geary one day\ndiscovered ore. His\nfrantic cable for help\nto an old comrade,\nJohn Stuart Webster,\nmining engineer, is\nthe jumpoff of a tale\nthat has many breath\nless moments for two\nmen and a girl.\nWebster\u2014\nMan\u2019s Man\nshows Peter B. Kyne,\nthe author, a wav\nfrom his native Cali\nfornia, but in a coun\ntry and among peo\nple that he Knows\nwell. For stirring,\nwholesome enterprise\nand a determina\ntion to come off with\nthe goods against all\nodds, we recommend\nWebster; also a cer\ntain young lady who\nhad much to do with\nhis fortunes.\nWatch for\nThis New Serial\nin These Columns!\nBreed sales as follows\nJ. C. HOLMES,\nSecretary-Treasurer, Brookings.\n\u00bba\n1\ni\nF\na u\nfor\nOKU\n10\nand\nf\nft 1\nwh\ninf\nbe\nBr<","height":"35716","width":"25888"}}
